# Deliverable 2 — Build, packaging, and release strategy

## Pipeline overview

Two artifact types, one constraint that shapes everything: every image, chart, and binary the appliance will ever need at runtime must be present in the artifact at the time it leaves Superna's build system. Nothing is fetched at install time.

![Build pipeline](Diagrams/PipelineFlow.png)

Bitbucket Pipelines orchestrates the build on self-hosted runners. Self-hosted runners are non-negotiable: OVA construction requires tens of gigabytes of disk space, access to a hypervisor toolchain (QEMU/KVM or VMware's OVF tool), and build times that would exhaust cloud runner quotas. Runners must be network-isolated from production but have internet access for pulling upstream images at build time.

The build stage does one thing most Kubernetes pipeline tutorials omit and that will silently break air-gapped deployments if missed: every Helm chart's default image references point at public registries (`registry.k8s.io`, `docker.io`, etc.). Before images are loaded into the Zot registry in the OVA, every chart's `values.yaml` and image reference is rewritten to point at the local Zot path. This rewrite happens once at build time and is baked into the chart tarballs inside the artifact. At runtime, every image pull goes to Zot — there are no fallback paths to public registries, by construction.

Scan and sign run as blocking pipeline stages: a scan failure stops promotion, not just flags a warning. JFrog Xray monitors Artifactory continuously after artifacts are stored — if a new CVE is disclosed against a dependency in a released artifact, Xray flags it and a rebuild is triggered automatically, as shown by the feedback loop in the pipeline diagram.

Promotion is a manual gate. Staging artifacts are immutable once signed; promotion is a metadata operation in Artifactory (staging → release repository), not a rebuild. Anything requiring a change after signing gets a new version number.

