## Offline / air-gapped installation

### Initial deploy

The customer downloads the OVA from Superna's customer portal to an internet-connected machine and transfers it to their environment by whatever mechanism the site permits (internal file share, USB drive, secure transfer). They import the OVA into vCenter using the standard OVF import wizard, fill in the vApp Options form (IP address, netmask, gateway, admin credential, optional VIP and NTP server), and power on the VM. The bootstrap flow described in Deliverable 1 runs autonomously. The customer has a working appliance without touching a keyboard during first boot.

For non-VMware OVF-capable hypervisors, the customer uses their hypervisor's equivalent import flow; cloud-init's generic OVF datasource reads configuration from the standard `ovf-env.xml` file that OVF-compatible tooling generates automatically.

### Multi-node expansion

Every node — control-plane or worker — deploys from the same OVA. The OVF properties include a `role` field and a `join-endpoint` field. An initialising node leaves both blank; the bootstrap agent creates a new cluster. A joining node sets `role` to `server` (second or third control-plane node) or `worker`, and sets `join-endpoint` to the first node's IP address plus the join token displayed by `arkctl cluster token`. No shell access between nodes, no shared state prior to join.

`arkctl node add --role server` enforces the 3-node control-plane floor and actively blocks a 2-node topology. Adding a second control-plane node without a third leaves the cluster unable to form quorum on either node's failure — worse than single-node.

### Adding a module

The customer downloads the module bundle from Superna's portal on an internet-connected machine, transfers it to the appliance (`scp` or equivalent), and runs `arkctl module install <bundle.tar.gz>`. No additional platform configuration required. Platform services (ingress, registry, identity, cert-manager) are already running from bootstrap.

