## Upgrade strategy

**In-place only.** This matches the delivery shape customers already know from Superna's legacy products and avoids the operational overhead of side-by-side deployments. The checkpointed upgrade sequence is described fully in Deliverable 1 (data flow, Flow 5): validate → OS snapshot → platform Helm upgrades → module upgrades (dependency order) → reboot into new snapshot → post-boot verify. Idempotent resume-from-last-checkpoint on any failure.

**Version skew policy.** Each upgrade bundle's manifest declares `version` (what it produces) and `min-required-version` (the oldest source version it upgrades from). For V1: each bundle supports upgrading from the immediately preceding minor version. A customer on v1.0 wanting v1.2 applies the v1.1 bundle, then v1.2 — two transfers, two maintenance windows. This simplifies the test matrix significantly (each bundle tested against one source version) and matches how Superna's existing products handle this. Cumulative bundles supporting arbitrary version jumps are on the roadmap for when sequential hops become a real operational burden at fleet scale.

**Rollback.** If post-upgrade verification fails, `arkctl upgrade rollback` reverses: Helm rollback for each module in reverse dependency order, Helm rollback for platform components, reboot into the previous Btrfs snapshot. PVC data is never rolled back — the Btrfs snapshot covers only the OS filesystem, not the volume mount paths. A rollback restores the platform; data written by modules during the upgrade window remains.

**Customer-driven, never push.** Upgrades are applied by the customer at a time they choose. Superna has no mechanism to push an upgrade to a customer's appliance — consistent with "no Superna-side control plane" and the "no phone-home" regulatory requirement.

