## Security and supply chain

**Artifact signing.** Every container image is signed with cosign at build time using a key managed in Infisical, before images are loaded into the OVA's Zot registry. The OVA and each upgrade bundle are signed as a whole (detached cosign signature alongside the artifact in Artifactory). `arkctl upgrade apply` verifies the bundle signature before extracting a single byte. Signature failure is a hard stop.

**SBOM.** syft generates a software bill of materials for every OVA and upgrade bundle, covering OS packages, binaries, and all container image layers. The SBOM is stored alongside the artifact in Artifactory and included inside the upgrade bundle so the customer retains it after download. Regulated customers can produce the SBOM for security questionnaires or compliance audits without contacting Superna support.

**CVE path.** JFrog Xray monitors Artifactory continuously. When a new CVE is disclosed against a dependency in a released artifact, Xray flags it and the pipeline rebuild is triggered automatically. The response sequence: triage the CVE against the ARK deployment context → update the affected dependency or base image → rebuild → full scan re-runs → new patch bundle cut and promoted → customer notification via customer portal. Time from CVE disclosure to patch bundle available is a KPI agreed with leadership before first customer ship (open question OQ-5 in the risk register).

**Promotion gates as the quality boundary.** Staging artifacts are test-grade; release artifacts are customer-grade. The promotion gate (manual, requiring security review and QA sign-off) is the only moment where a staging artifact becomes a release artifact. There is no emergency bypass — a security-critical patch still goes through the gate, which is why keeping the gate fast matters as much as keeping it rigorous.
